===Verb===
{{en-verb|weds|wedding|wed|past2=wedded}}

# {{lb|en|transitive}} To perform the [[marriage]] ceremony for; to join in [[matrimony]].
#: ''The priest '''wed''' the couple.''
#* Milton
#*: And Adam, '''wedded''' to another Eve, / Shall live with her.
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To take as one's [[spouse]].
#: ''She '''wed''' her first love.''
#* '''2017''' September 27, David Browne, "[http://www.rollingstone.com/culture/news/hugh-hefner-playboy-founder-dead-at-91-w443922 Hugh Hefner, 'Playboy' Founder, Dead at 91]," ''Rolling Stone''
#*:  In 1989, he '''wed''' Playmate Kimberley Conrad, a marriage that ended in 2010. In 2013, he married his younger girlfriend, Crystal Harris, with whom he was still '''wed''' at the time of his death. 
# {{lb|en|intransitive}} To take a spouse.
# {{lb|en|figuratively|transitive}} To [[join]] or [[commit]] to, more or less permanently, as if in marriage.
#: ''I'm not '''wedded''' to this proposal; suggest an alternative.''
#* Shakespeare
#*: Thou art '''wedded''' to calamity.
#* Tillotson
#*: Men are '''wedded''' to their lusts.
#* '''2008''', Bradley Simpson, ''Economists with Guns'', page 72:
#*: {{...}} the PPS paper proposed a political doctrine that '''wedded''' modernization theory to U.S. support for national security states {{...}}
# {{lb|en|figurative|intransitive}} To take to oneself and support; to [[espouse]].
#* Clarendon
#*: They positively and concernedly '''wedded''' his cause.
# {{lb|en|Northern England|Scotland}} To [[wager]], [[stake]], [[bet]], [[place]] a [[bet]], [[make]] a [[wager]].
#: {{ux|en|I'd '''wed''' my head on that.}}

